# `GET /api/podcast/related-to-tv`

Returns up to `limit` podcasts related to a TV show, projected as
`MCPodcastItem` JSON. Discovery uses the public Apple iTunes Search API and
crosswalks `collectionId` → PodcastIndex feed via the `itunes_id` field
indexed on `idx:podcasts` (see `idx-podcasts-itunes-id-deploy-plan.mdc`).

## Request

| Param  | Type   | Required | Default | Notes |
|--------|--------|----------|---------|-------|
| `mc_id` | string | yes | — | TV show mc_id, e.g. `tmdb_1399`. Document must exist in Redis with `mc_type == "tv"`. |
| `limit` | int    | no  | `5` | `1..50`. Caps the returned array. |

## Response

`200 OK` — JSON array (possibly empty) of `MCPodcastItem` documents
serialized with `model_dump(mode="json")`. The `id` field is the integer
PodcastIndex feed id; `mc_id` is the auto-generated `podcast_<feed_id>`
form (matches what the rest of the podcast API returns).

Error responses:

| Status | When |
|--------|------|
| `400`  | `mc_id` resolves to a document whose `mc_type` is not `tv` |
| `404`  | No Redis document for `mc_id`, or document has no usable title |
| `500`  | Redis read failed |
| `502`  | Apple iTunes Search API call failed (network/HTTP error) |

## Resolution flow

1. `mc_id` → Redis key via `_redis_key_for_id` (yields `media:{mc_id}`),
   then `JSON.GET` the document. The TV title is read from `title`,
   falling back to `search_title`.
2. Call Apple iTunes Search API:
   `GET https://itunes.apple.com/search?term={title}+tv+show&media=podcast&limit={limit*4|>=25}`.
   The `limit*4` over-fetch absorbs candidates whose `collectionId` is not
   present in `idx:podcasts` (~11% of PodcastIndex feeds have no
   `itunes_id`).
3. For each iTunes result with a numeric `collectionId`, run
   `FT.SEARCH idx:podcasts '@itunes_id:[{cid} {cid}]' LIMIT 0 1` via
   `RedisRepository.search_podcasts`. Skip iTunes results that don't match
   any indexed podcast.
4. Convert each matched JSON document with
   `api.podcast.core.redis_doc_to_mc_podcast_item` and append to the
   response array, dedup'd by `mc_id`. Stop once `limit` items have been
   collected.

## Conversion helper: `redis_doc_to_mc_podcast_item`

Lives in `src/api/podcast/core.py`. Translates a Redis `idx:podcasts` JSON
document into an `MCPodcastItem` for API responses, normalizing two
historical inconsistencies:

- `MCPodcastItem.id` is the integer feed id, sourced from the document's
  `source_id` string (the document's `id` field is the namespaced
  `podcastindex_podcast_{feed_id}` form).
- `categories` is stored as a `dict[str, str]` by the legacy bulk loader
  but as a normalized `list[str]` by the nightly ETL. The helper accepts
  either and yields a `dict[str, Any]` (lists are coerced to a positional
  dict) so `MCPodcastItem` validation never fails on shape drift.

## Local testing

`scripts/test_podcasts_related_to_tv.py` is a thin async client around the
endpoint. Two modes:

```bash
# One-shot
make test-podcasts-related-to-tv MC_ID=tmdb_1399 LIMIT=10

# Equivalent direct invocation
python scripts/test_podcasts_related_to_tv.py tmdb_1399 --limit 10

# Just titles, one per line
make test-podcasts-related-to-tv MC_ID=tmdb_1399 TITLES=1

# Interactive: omit positional mc_id, type queries `mc_id [limit]` per line
python scripts/test_podcasts_related_to_tv.py
```

The script defaults to `http://localhost:9001` (override with `--host` /
`HOST=`). It prints the request line and the JSON array (or error body) and
exits non-zero on any HTTP error so it composes with shell pipelines / CI.

## Dependencies

- `idx:podcasts` must have `$.itunes_id` indexed as `NUMERIC SORTABLE`. See
  `idx-podcasts-itunes-id-deploy-plan.mdc` for the per-environment
  `FT.ALTER` requirement; without it, this endpoint will always return
  `[]`.
- Apple iTunes Search API is unauthenticated but soft rate-limited
  (~20 req/min/IP). No caching is applied at the route layer; if traffic
  warrants caching, layer it with `RedisCache` keyed on the normalized
  TV title (not on `mc_id`, since multiple `mc_id`s can share a title).

## Deployment

This is a pure code change in `web/app.py` and `src/api/podcast/core.py`.
There is **no** schema migration, no new index, no new env var, and no new
secret. Standard Cloud Run deploy of the web/API service is sufficient.

### Pre-deploy checks

| Environment | `idx:podcasts.itunes_id` indexed? | Action |
|---|---|---|
| Public / prod (GCE `redis-stack-vm`) | Yes (PR #98 already deployed) | None |
| Local dev (Docker `localhost:6380`) | Apply once if not done | `redis-cli -p 6380 FT.ALTER idx:podcasts SCHEMA ADD '$.itunes_id' AS itunes_id NUMERIC SORTABLE` (see `idx-podcasts-itunes-id-deploy-plan.mdc`) |
| Cloud Run web service env | n/a (uses public Redis above) | None |

If `itunes_id` is not indexed in the target Redis, the endpoint silently
returns `[]` for every request. Verify with
`FT.INFO idx:podcasts | grep itunes_id` before deploying anywhere new.

### Deploy

```bash
# Web/API service only — endpoint lives here
make deploy-web
```

`deploy-web` runs `scripts/deploy_web_cr.sh` which builds the container and
deploys the `media-circle-search` Cloud Run service (dev environment).
No restart of the ETL VM or Redis VM is required.

### Post-deploy verification

Replace `<host>` with the deployed Cloud Run URL (or
`http://localhost:9001` for local).

```bash
# Sanity: route is registered (expect 422 from missing required mc_id)
curl -sS -o /dev/null -w "%{http_code}\n" "<host>/api/podcast/related-to-tv"

# Real check: known TV mc_id should return a JSON array (possibly empty)
curl -sS "<host>/api/podcast/related-to-tv?mc_id=tmdb_1399&limit=5" | jq .

# Same thing via the test script
make test-podcasts-related-to-tv MC_ID=tmdb_1399 LIMIT=5 HOST=<host>
make test-podcasts-related-to-tv MC_ID=tmdb_1399 LIMIT=10 TITLES=1 HOST=<host>
```

Expected: `200` with a JSON array of `MCPodcastItem` documents. An empty
array for a popular show is the canary that `idx:podcasts.itunes_id` is not
indexed in the Redis the service is pointed at.

### Rollback

Standard Cloud Run revision rollback — no data side effects, no schema to
revert. Reverting the commit and redeploying also works.
